{"/service/ndnp/wyu/batch_wyu_frannie_ver01/data/sn86072160/00514150369/1921032401/0698.xml":{"full_text":"PAGE TWO\nOc Casper Daily tribune\nIssued every evening .accept Sunday at Casper. Natrona\nCounty, Wyo. Pubilcation Offices: Tribune Building\nBUSINESS TELEPHONES 15 and 1\u00ab\nBranch Telephone Exchange Connecting All Departments\nEntered at Casper. (Wyoming) Postofflce as second -class\nmatter. November 22, 1916.\nW\u00bbrpvo Ti\u00a3S oufrcq\nREPORTS FROM UNITED PRESS\nJ. E. HANWAY\u2014 President and Editor\nEARL H. HANWAY Business Manager\nW. 11. HUNTLEY-Associate Editor\nR. E. EVANS City Editor\nTHOMAS DAILY -Advertising Manager\nAdvertising Representatives\nDavid J. Randall. 341 Fitth Ave., New York City\nPrudden. King A Prudden, 1720-23 Steger Bldg.. Chicago.\n111. Copies of the Daily Tribuno are on file in ths New\nYork and Chicago offices and visitors are welcome.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nBy Carrier\nOne Year\nSix Months 3 J*\"\nThree Months l-*\u00bb\nOne Month\nPer Copy\nBy Mail\nOne Year\nSix Months 3 r?\nThree Months\nNo subscription by erzoptei! for ICXS period than\nthi-ua months.\nAll subscription j must be paid In advance sn<\u2019 he\nDaily Tribune will not insure delivery after\ntion becomes one month in arrears.\nMember of Audit Bureau of Circulations (A. B. C.)\nMember of the Associated Press\nThe Associated Press is exclusively entitled to the\nuse for publication of all news credited in this paper and\nalso the local news published 1. rein.\nKick if You Don't Get Tour Tribune.\nCall IS or 10 any time after G o\u2019clock If you fall to\nreceive your Tribune. A paper will be delivered to you\nby special messenger. Make it yobr duty to let The\nTribune know when your carrier misses you.\nPAYING OUR DEBTS.\nThere is no one who doubts the stupendous task\nconfronting the special session of congress in solv\ning the tax problems that will make themselves the\nfirst order of business. There is a promise to the\npeople arising out of the campaign that cannot be ig\nnored. Abolition of some features and relief from\nburdens in others is what is expected. How it is all\nto be accomplished and still secure sufficient revenue\nto maintain the government is the hardest nut any\nAmerican congress has yet had to crack. The sources\nof revenue are not producing the public requirements\nas it is because of the present state of business and\nwith something like six billions running expenses to\nmeet we may well view the situation with serious\nness.\nThen when it is known that to successfully carry\nout the fiscal policy necessitates financing in the\ntotal of seventeen billions of dollars within the next\ntwo years. Where is the money all coming from*\nA change in tariff system from a free trade basis to\na protective basis with higher rates will of course aid\nbut only in millions where billions are required.\nTalk, then is in endless amount. Specific plans of\naction there is none. Pass it all on-to the people in\ntax burdens tho new with the old is in effect all that\nhas been suggested. The form may be modified but\nin the end the people pay, while the people are cry\ning for relief. It will be dangerous to drive them\nfurther and the fact should be recognized.\nPolitical turnovers are the easiest thing the people\naccomplish when aroused. The proof is of too rc\noccurrence to require mention. The people ex\npected relief, were promised relief and they voted for\nrelief. They must have it. Faith must not be broken.\nAn elimination of indebtedness removes the neces\nsity of heavy taxation to pay interest and principal.\nAnd the first place to strike is the depreciated war\nbond issues. Upon the twenty billion issued by the\ntime the people have redeemed them they will have\npaid a total of fifty billions.\nWould It be better to sweat out that inconceivable\nsum df money by labor or would it be good sense to\nsquare it off now by disposing of a share of the pub\nlic resources of coal, oil, land, water power, minerals\nand other valuables that will do more public good in\nprivate hands than lying dormant in public owner\nship?\nYou can never tell where the next school scandal\nis going to break out. The Denver affair would not\nhave occurred if fathers and mothers showed proper\nparental interest and exercised befitting control over\ntheir children out of school hours and co-operated\nwith teachers to sufficient extent to know what was\ngoing forward during school sessions. If you stave\nno interest in your own boys and girls don\u2019t expect\nanybody else to have more concern than you show.\nA very noted educator, having served as superin\ntendent of public schools at Boston and Cincinnati,\nsays the trouble with public schools is the fact that\nteachers are \u201ctrying to make the children fit a stand\nardized suit of clothes, called curriculum, which can\nnot be done successfully.\u201d Is the gentleman right,\nwe wonder?\nINTERNATIONAL AMENITIES.\nThere are some very entertaining contributions to\nthe gaiety of nations these days on the part of inter\nnational correspondents. One would assume that we\nhad actually entered upon an era of open diplom\nacy, openly arrived at, so familiarly are the hopes\nand fears of nations treated. We know better, how\never, and when strifes and misunderstandings are an\nnounced between France and Britain, to at least sea\nson the statements with salt before accepting them.\nWe are informed of an Anglo-French rupture\nthreatening European reconstruction, serious wo are\nassured, so serious, that tho premiers of the respect\nive powers have gone before their parliamentary\nbodies to explain that the recent harmony gathering\nin London to discuss final touches to reparations was I\nno harmony convention at all. It was right spirited\nat the close and more so after adjournment when\nreckoning was taken of results and the discovery\nmade that Britain had annexed about all of the eco\nnomic advantages to be derived through the confer\nence and left the illusions of military glory to France.\nIf these boys do not know each other well enough\nby this time they have no business engaging in the\ngame of diplomatic poker. It is the poorest sports\nmanship in the world to squack about the matter when\nyou get the worst of it. Look what we got when\nfriend Wilson crossed over to sit in the game. Are\nwo beefing about tho trimming he received? We\u2019ll\nsay not. We simply decline to sit in again. The game\nis crooked and we don\u2019t play it that way. The con\nsistent declinations we have returned to the numer\nous pressing invitations extended ought to be suf\nficient hint of what we think of European poker\nparties.\nThe strained relations of France and Britain have\nsped M. Viviani across the sea to seek counsel and\ncomfort from the well-known United States and add\nhe may to the fires of friendship long boast\ned by the sister republics.\nM. Viviani is welcome to our hospitable shores. We\ncan entertain him, dine him, but alas! we cannot\nwine him unless Mr. Harding can resurrect some of\nthe private stock the government stored against the\njay of drought. He will learn, however, after he has\nl lived in our atmosphere a few days, that our people\nI will take no part in European concerts, poker fes\ntivitics, or parties of any description. We are not\nonly through, but we ere done. We are proceeding\nto attend to an accumulated lot of our own business.\nMr. Daugherty says Mr. Palmer was right, beer is\na medicine. People who know different may derive\nsome amusement observing the psychological effect.\nMedicine never attained any cyeat decree popu\nlarity with the generality of folks. It may not have\ndone so even under another name. But beer mas\nquerading under the name of medicine may grow in\nto as deep disfavor as medicine has always enjoyed.\n0\nThank Heaven, Clara and her nasty little old story\nare not to be exploited in the moviea. Tho play\nwrights will not write it and the producers win not\nproduce. That ought to very nearly shut her out.\nDodging automobiles is regarded as a very health\nful exercise. But you must be successful in order to\nretain your health.\nStrange as it may seem, Germany has a few friends\nleft on earth.\nTHZ UNCLEAN THING.\n\u201cThe puzzling question whether the soviet govern\nment or Mr. Lloyd George has been more deepely\ntaken in,\u201d suggests the New York Tribune, \u201cby the'\nagreement signed for the reopening of trade between\nGreat Britain and Russia may be answered in two\nways. In so far as the agreement was put through\nin the guilelessness of good faith both have been\ntaken in over their heads; but if the two parties to\nthe agreement fully understood\u2014-as we suppose they\nmust have understood\u2014that the things they have\ncovenanted to do are impossible, then neither was\ntaken in. If that was the case, Sir Robert Home and\nMr. Krassine, of course, exchanged appropriate winks\nacross the table.\n\u201cThe conditions solemnly agreed to in Urf? treaty\nare impossible of fulfillment because the industries of\nRussia having be6n destroyed under the soviet rule\nshe has fiO commodities to exchange with the British\nmerchants and must pay with gold for the goods she\nimports. It is known to all the world that Russia has\nvery little gold except stolen gold or gold already\npledged. Moreover, debts are owing to British mer\nchants which they could not collect from Russia, and\nthe representative of the soviets was unable to per\nsuade the British government that gold arriving in\npayment for goods to be shipped in the fixture\nbe regarded as immune from seizure to pay these\nearlier claims. Mr. Krassine had to consent that if\nthe gold coming from his country were seized the mat\nter would have to be left to the decision of tho Brit\nish courts, which have already adjudicated such\nclaims in favor of British creditors.\u201d\nMy, but the dames in tho quiet and cultured Capi\ntol Hill section of the nation\u2019s capital are touchy.\nThey recently heard by night the raucous sounds* of\njazz syncopating to the newest shimmy, somewhere in\nthat quiet and aristocratic environ and immediately\ngot the police out to abate the nuisance. Tut, tut!\nas Woodrow was wont to say.\nThe state of Nevada will in future \u201cgas\u201d her con\ndemned criminals. That fixes them, but what about\nthe other condemned folks who foregather at Reno. Is\nthere no lethal treatment to put them out of misery?\nFrom the returns it would seem that there are a\nfew fans ddvoted to the national pastime still in Cas\nper\u2014or not so still either.\nWestern Europe also needs rain. Boy, page Her\nbert Hoover.\nTHE LIQUOR LAWS.\n\u201cOne of the greatest mysteries about the Volstead\nact,\u201d states the Indianapolis News, \u201cis why there\nshould be any mystery about it. It should be pos\nsible to enact a law about which there is no doubt\u2014\na law that says plainly what it means and is not sus\nceptible of change every time someone clothed with\nlegal authority takes a fresh look at it. The ruling\nmade by A. Mitchell Palmer shortly before he left\nthe office of attorney general has upset the system\nof the prohibition enforcement officials and a revis\nion of methods will be necessary. Attorney General\nDaugherty shows no disposition to review the Palmer\nruling, and it is presumed that it will stand. The\ncourts eventually will decide the question.\n\u201cThe purpose of the prohibition amendment was to\nstop the manufacture and sale of intoxicating liquors\nfor beverage purposes. The constitutional amend\nment had to be supplemented by legislation provid\ning for its enforcement. Mr. Palmer has ruled that\nthe enforcement statutes do not prevent the unlimited\nmanufacture and sale of wine, beer and whisky for\nmedicinal purposes.\u201d\no\nIf Mr. Secretary Davis succeeds in adjusting the\ncontroversy between the packers and their employes\nand at the same time conserves the interests of the\npublic ho will have done a great day\u2019s work.\no\nFormer President Taft warns that increasing the\npublic debt by the adoption of bonus legislation will\ndefer restoration of normal times to a remote period.\nThe appearance of British war ships in German har\nbors will have what sort of effect on reparation mat\nters do you guess?\nIn the interest of \u201csound economics\u201d it is suggest\ned that France and Germany quit their quarreling and\nget tp work.\ntyUST TRAVEL SAME PATH.\nThe Orange Judd Farmer, in the language of tho\nstreet \u201csaid a mouthful\u201d when it remarked:\nSlow business, closed shops and mills, reduced rail\nroad operation, wage cuts, strikes, and unemployment\nare met with in every direction. Tbe farmer was\nmade the goat six months ago, but the rest are get\nting theirs now. And however much the farmer may\nsympathize with other people in their troubles, ho\ncannot forget the fact that the rest must travel the\npath that he was forced to walk in before we shall\nreach the level of economic equality that must pre\ncede any return of prosperity for anybody.\nHo does not call to Capital and Labor, shivering on\nthe bank: \u201cCome in, the water is fine,\u201d but he does\nsay: \u201cPlunge in and get it over with.\u201d All the bricks\nin the row have got to topple alike, and the sooner\nit is over with the better.\nNice time to talk about Philippine independence\nwhen the rule of Governor General Harrison has\npractically destroyed the advancement made by pre\nvious American administrations.\nNever mind, the children can roll their Easter eggs\non the White House lawn this year, just like they did\nbefore a certain Democratic president turned it into\na sheep pasture.\nWo flatter ourselves that we are lew crude and\nblood-thirsty than our neighbors to the south, yet we\nput over our bull fights every day.\n\u201cPresident Harding,\u201d says his caddy, \u201cis just like\nthe rest of them. Chesty when he makes a good shot,\nhas an alibi when be dabs.\u201d\nI Where do our friends on the other side of Atlantic\nget this \u201csound economics\u201d stuff in their view of debt\ncancellation?\nepe Casper g>atq> ettoune\n\\WITHOUR WYOMING\nAccept Sliding Scale\n(Wheatland Times!\nLocal manager G. T. Goodrich, re\nporta that farmers are accepting the\nproposition of the Great Western\nGctsnu* eemtmny. most of them taking\nthe eliding scale contract, a few pre\nferring the flat rate.. It now appears\nlikely that the usual acreage will be\nplanted to beets in this vicinity. Many\nof the larger growers consider that\nthe contracts offered aesure tbe farmer\nbetter returns than can be realized on\nany other farm crop. They feel, too,\nthat it la to the interest of al! land\nowners to devote as large an acreage\nas possible to sugar beets for by so\ndoing, increasing the acreage each\nyear, it will soon bring X sugar fac\ntory to Wheatland, which would add\nmuch to the yearly profits of the beet\ngrower besides bringing other advan\ntages of great benefit to the farming\ncommunity at large.\nMr. Goodrich advises that seed win\nbe received about the first of April.\nAnyone Intending to raise beets should\nmake it known promptly in order that\ntheir b\u2014A may be provided. About\n1,100 acres have been contracted up\nto date.\nTesting New Law.\n(Laramie Republican)\nTho injunction proceedings of John\nW. Sigman. marshal, against G.\nHardy and Pearl Parks, to have their\nrespective places of residence declared\nnuisances, and to have been heard\ntoday, were continued until tomorrow\nin the district court. They Were set\nfor hearing before Judge Mentzer,\nwho was to have sat for Judge Tid\nball, but a change came and an or\nder is being sought from Judge Ment\nzer transferring jurisdiction to Judge\nTldball. F. E. Anderson, attorney for\nthe defendants, has filed a demurer\nto the petition, attacking the consti\ntutionality of tho law, passed at the\nrecent session of the legislature, un\nder which the proceedings are brot.\nand this will be argued when the\ncases come on to be'heard.\nfor Tourists.\n(Saratoga Sun)\nSomeone who has a surplus of\nroom about town can make money\nthia year by providing tent houses to\nrent to tourists who wish to remain\nhere for a few weeks or months. The\nlocal club secretary has received in\nquiries from several parties asking\nabout what accommodations can be\nhad here In the way of cabins, cot\ntages or tent houses during the sum\nmer season, and it is likely that such\naccommodations could be easily rent\ncd during the summer at good price.\nThe town Is now filled up to a point\nwhere there is hardly a house that\ncan bo rented, and comfortably ar\nranged tent houses in a desirable lo\ncation will be at a. premium this sea\nson.\nSmall Vote Recorded.\n(Sheridan Enterprise)\nWith only 12 votes against it, and\n147 for it, tho 1150,000 school bond\nissue for the completion of the new\nCentral school, and to care for other\nwork needed in the local school sy\u00bb-\ntcrti was declared carried by the di\nrectors of Sheridan's school district\nNo. 7 Saturday afternoon.\nThe polls were open three hours,\nfrom 2 until 5 o'clock, and the vote\nwas considered good, although the\nI\nI MOTOR CAR\nA You will find every member\nof the family loyal to the car. y\nQ 2\no It is serviceable tffike for all g\nages and all demands, whether\nbusiness, family or social. J\n\n3 The gasoline consumption is unusually low.\nThs tire mileage is unusually high.\nI\nColiseum Motor Company\nCASPER, WYO.\n131 Ea.t Fifth Phone 724 i\nI j\u2019\u2019/'* I\nj Lf** uii li'irii'Tii'ii II li~~i n ii'.h ihi 11 li nnj n\"n iggl.il IL'bit S\nvote shows that few persons inter\nested themselves in consideration of\nthe matter either way.\nAs predicted by the school board\nthere was little opposition to the elec\ntion. although csveral expressions of\ndissatisfaction with the issue had\nbeen expressed.\nBuys Dairy Cattle.\n(Douglas Enterprise)\nM. S. Johnson returned yesterday\nmorning from a business trip to Den\nver where he purchased fifty-six head\nof Holstaih cows and heifers. Mr.\nJohnson says these cattle are among\nthe best he bus ever seen and some Os\nthem give si much as six gallons of\nmilk per day. He is planning on\nbuilding up one of the largest dairy\nherds in the state this spring.\nr. t wit th? r.fmgM\u00dfsaa\nQuestion Box\n(Any reader can get the answer to\nany question by writing Tho Casper\nDaily Tribune Information Bureau.\nFrederic J. Haskin, Director, Washing\nton, D. C. This offer applies strictly\nto information. The Bureau cannot at\ntempt to settle domestic troubles, nor\nto undertake exhaustive research on\nany subject. Write your question\nplainly and briefly. Give full name\nand address and enclose two cents in\nstamps for return postage. All re\nplies are eent direct to the inquirer.)\nQ. What is the present value of\nthe German mark?\u2014W. G.\nA, The German idJirk is Trcrih\nabout one-half cent in American\nmoney. The exact amount fluctuates,\nhowever, in accordance with the ex\nchange market. The pre-war value\nwas almost 24 cents.\nQ. Does New York lead In the pro\nduction of buckwheat?\u2014S. W. K.\nA. In 1019 Pennsylvania led ail\nstates with a production Os 5,530,000\nbushels of buckwheat. New York was\nsecond with 5,126,000 bushels.\nQ. Why do some gold fish have\nblack spots, while others do not?\u2014\nH. L. L.\nA. The' Bureau of Fisheries says\nthat it is natural for young gold fish\nto have black spots. As they grow\nolder these disappear.\nQ. What is meant by a \u201cPublish\ners\u2019 Doxen\u201d?\u2014G. H. S.\nA. A publishers* dozen la 13 copies.\nThis phrase doubtless arose from the\nearly custom of a baker to allow 13\nrolls to each dozen sold\u2014a custom\nthat later found its way into tho\nwholesale book trade.\nQ. Who was called \u201cThe Dumb\nOx\u201d?\u2014G. W. C.\nA. This was a nickname applied to\nThomas Aquinas, while he was study\ning in Cologne in 1246 under Albert\nthe Great. The epithet applied to his\nsilence, and Albert is said to have\npredicted \u201cthat tho ox would one day\nfill the world with his bellowing.\u201d\nQ. Can cabbages be put in a silo\nto use for feed for cattle?\u2014L. W. K.\nA. An experiment conducted by\nthe Department of Agriculture show\ned that while cabbages in their natu-\nnil state are acceptable to cattle, the\nsiloed product which resembles un\nsalted sauer kraut la not eaten. Thia\nexperiment did not contemplate forc\ning the animals through hunter, or\nby repeated attempts.\nQ. What are the five largest cities\nin the United States?\u2014l. M.\nA. According to the 1930 census\nthe following are the five target cities\nin the United States: New York City,\nN. Y.; Chicago, IU.; Philadelphia, Pa.;\nDetroit, Mich.*, Cleveland, Ohio.\n(t What is implied when referring\nto a person as \"The Admirable Crich\nton?\u201d How is Crichton pronounced?\u2014\nC. C. H.\nA. James Crichton was a Scotch\nprodigy of the sixteenth century.\nHence this appellation would indi\ncate a person of great accomplish-\nOTHER CITIES DECLARE\nFOR MANAGER PLAN, WHY\nNOT GIVE IT A TRIAL?\nHays, Kansas,\nMarch 4, 1921.\nMr. Charles B. Stafford,\nSecretary-Manager,\nChamber of Commerce,\nCasper, Wyoming.\nDear Sir. We are glad to say that\nHays likes the city manager form 6t\ngovernment. It is not a panacea for\nall ills, of course, but it is a long\nstop forward. Much depends upon\ngetting the right kind of a manager,\njust as it does in any business. But\n\u00abur\u00ably, a corporation of the size of\naur cities oan afford to look far and\nwide and secure the very best ex\neoutive possible for this purpose\nUnder the aiderman ic form of gov\nernment, Hays was continually run\nning behind in its expenditures, had\nto issue unpaid warrants drawing 8\nor 7 per cent interest; the light and\nwater works did not pay operating\nexpenses, though from inefficient ac\ncounting, they had thought it was.\nThe city now pays as it goes, dis\ncounts all bills, operates light and\nwater departments, on a paying\nbasis, based on ALL operating ex\npense\u2014interest on bonds, deprecia\ntion, insurance, repairs and exten\nsions. The plants operate more eco\nnomically and efficiently and give\nmuch better service. Special and\nfree patrons have been eliminated\nand politics Absolutely abolished.\nIn our city, the manager is also a\ncivil and electrical engineer, and this\nis a very desirable combination, espe\ncially in small towns. This makes\nus safe from graft on large con\ntracts for public works, as all con-\nSIMPLE COMBINATION\nHELPS WEAK EYES\nChspor people are astonished at the\nquick restilts produced by simple\nwitch hazel, camphor, hydraetls. etc.,\nas mixed in Lavoptik eye wash. In\none cose of weak and nearsighted\neyes a few days* use brought great im\nprovement. In another case it stop\nped eye pains and inflammation. We\nguarantee a small bottle of Levoptlk\nto help ANY CASE wook, strained\nor inflamed eyes. Aluminum eye cup\nFREE. Casper Pharmacy\u2014Adv.\nmeats. The name is pronounced S 3 j\nif spelled Cry ton. 1\nA. Io hw do Im> pwMna onnsUknMi\na multitude?\u2014A. A. I\nA. AceortUng to some ancient le\ngal authorities \u201cat least ten\u201d were 1\nrequired to make a multitude.\nQ. Hew is Sian Feta nsu\u2014\n\u2014A. C.-T.\n-A. The Society of Friends of Irish\nFreedom who rspremsnt ths Sinn Fein\norganization in America say that the\nproper pronunciation of the word Sinn\nFein is \"Shin Fane.\u201d\nQ. Can anything be done to de\nstroy the burnt taste of scorched\nmilk?\u2014ML 8. W.\nA. Remove the milk at once from\nthe stove and plane the pan in a ba-\nsin of cold water. Add a pinch Os\ntracts for public works aro under\nthe direct supervision of the man\nager and the specifications must be\nmet as stated.\nThe city manager reports to the\ncity commissioners each month all\ndetails of the operation of each of\nthe various departments water,\nlight, sewer, street and sidewalks,\neto.f so that they are at all times in\nformed just how the city stands\nfinancially and what improvements\noan be made, the aim being always\ntoward efficiency and economy, con\nsistent with service.\nif we can assist you in any way\nby more daa, please let us know,\nas wo are very glad to help spread\nthe idea of businesslike administra\ntion of our cities.\nVery truly yours,\n(Signed) RUTH FLIEOBACH,\nTo Make Easter a\nHappy Day for You\nAN EXTRA SPECIAL\nSale of 1,000 Lukls\u2019 Original and Famous\nPecan Nut 7E p\nLoaves\nWill Be Sold Next\nSATURDAY ONLY\n$1.50 Is the Usual Price\nNo Easter will be complete without one\nCome early before they are all gone\nThe Lukis Candy Co.\nComer Second and Wolcott\nWatch for our big offer in next Saturday\u2019s\npaper\nIs It Dangerous\nfor a Young Girl to\nGet Into the Movies?\nDo you want to get Into-the movies? Do\nyou know how to go about it? Read what\nthe president of four motion picture\ncompanies tells about the fascination of\nscreen work, its temptations and dangers.\n\u2014READ\u2014\n\u201cHOW TO GET INTO THE MOVIES\u201d\n\u2014IN\u2014\nFOR APRIL.\ng Chit To-day\nCHAS. M. GUNNISON\nANNOUNCEMENT\nThe undersigned Physicians and Dentists wish to\nannounce the removal of their offices to\nRooms 304 to 31 1\nInclusive\nMidwest Refining Co. Building\nCorner of Wolcott and East Second Streets\nCasper, Wyoming\nTelephones 1660 and 1651\nDK. J. C. KAMP\nDR. T. J. DREW\nDR. C. H. BAILEY\nDR. T. J. RIACH\nDR. K. C. MacPHERSON\nTHURSDAY, MARCH 24, 1921\n*U UU ,tlr. This will parLall, U\nnot entirely destroy the burnt taste.\nQ. What causes the tinglrg noise\nLn wood when it is burning?-\u2014S. C.\nA. The singing of logs while burn\ning is due to the sap in the wood and\nthe pores, which aro air space.\nttOMn A\u00a3ENT LEAVES.\nCharles J. Rico, manager of the\nmunicipal buying department of Boa\nworth, Chanute Co., who succeeded\nin buying |855,000 worth of bonds at\na recent meeting of the city council,\nleft yesterday for Chicago, where he\nwill confer on matters pertaining to\nthe bond Issue with Wood A Oakley,\nattorneys, having a national reputa\ntion for passing on bonds.\n\u25a0\u2014Subscribe for The Tribune\nZuiciwX\nVSTRIKEJ\nCIGARETTE\nNo olgarette has\nthe same delicious\nflavor as Lucky\nStrike. Because\nLucky Strike Is the\ntoasted cigarette.","height":"19512","width":"16272"}}
